# Technology Stack & Desktop GUI Requirements

**Version**: 1.0  
**Date**: March 26, 2026  
**Status**: Requirements Stage (Implementation Pending)

---

## Executive Summary

App.TaskSequencer Phase 2 introduces a modern distributed architecture combining Orleans distributed actors, Aspire cloud orchestration, and a native Windows 11 desktop GUI. The desktop application provides local sequence visualization, deadline reporting, and iterative refinement monitoring.

---

## Technology Decisions & Rationale

### 1. Orleans 8.x

**Why Orleans?**
- Virtual actor model ideal for independent task calculations
- Built-in grain persistence and reminders
- Distributed transaction support (not needed here but available)
- Rich monitoring/diagnostics
- Microsoft-backed, production-tested in Azure services

**Key Orleans Packages**:
```xml
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Orleans.Server" Version="8.*" />
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Orleans.Core" Version="8.*" />
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting" Version="8.*" />
```

**Grain State Persistence** (Phase 2: memory-only, Phase 3+: SQLite/Azure Table Storage):
```csharp
// Phase 2: In-memory state
siloBuilder.UseDashboard(options => { ... })
           .ConfigureApplicationParts(parts => { ... });

// Phase 3: Persistent state
siloBuilder.AddSqliteGrainStorage("grain-storage", options => { ... });
```

---

### 2. Microsoft Aspire

**Why Aspire?**
- Unified development experience for distributed apps
- ServiceRegistry for inter-service discovery
- Local dashboard showing service health
- Environment variable injection
- Container orchestration abstractions ready

**Usage in Phase 2**:
- Orchestrates Orleans silo startup
- Hosts Orleans silo in console application or Windows service
- Provides local development dashboard
- Manages configuration injection

**Key Aspire Packages**:
```xml
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting" Version="8.*" />
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Extensions.ServiceDiscovery" Version="8.*" />
```

**Local Development**:
```bash
# Desktop app starts & initializes Orleans silo locally
dotnet run --project DesktopApp/DesktopApp.csproj
# Orleans silo embedded in desktop process
# All calculations happen locally, no network calls
```

---

### 3. WinUI 3 Desktop Application

**Why WinUI 3?**
- Modern Microsoft XAML framework for Windows 11
- Native Win32 performance
- Fluent Design System (modern Windows aesthetics)
- Direct integration with .NET 8
- Recommended by Microsoft for new Windows applications
- Exceptional tooling in Visual Studio
- Hardware-accelerated rendering

**Why NOT Web/ASP.NET Core?**
- Desktop application is completely local (no server needed)
- Simpler deployment (single .exe/.msix)
- No CORS, authentication, or HTTP complexity
- Direct access to Orleans grains (in-process)
- Native Windows integration (file pickers, notifications, etc.)

**Architecture**:
```
WinUI 3 Desktop App (MainWindow.xaml)
    ├─ ViewModels (MVVM pattern)
    │  ├─ DashboardVM
    │  ├─ TimelineVM
    │  ├─ GroupsVM
    │  └─ ViolationsVM
    ├─ Services
    │  └─ GrainClientService (Orleans integration)
    ├─ Orleans Silo (embedded)
    │  ├─ IExecutionInstanceGrain
    │  ├─ IExecutionPlanOrchestratorGrain
    │  ├─ ISequenceGroupGrain
    │  └─ IReportGeneratorGrain
    └─ CSV Parsing (Phase 1 reused)
```

**Key Packages**:
```xml
<!-- WinUI 3 / Windows App SDK -->
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.WindowsAppSDK" Version="1.5.*" />
<PackageReference Include="CommunityToolkit.Mvvm" Version="8.*" />
<PackageReference Include="CommunityToolkit.WinUI.Controls.DataGrid" Version="8.*" />

<!-- Windows integration -->
<PackageReference Include="CommunityToolkit.WinUI" Version="8.*" />
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Windows.SDK.BuildTools" Version="10.*" />

<!-- Orleans client (embedded in process, not remote) -->
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Orleans.Client" Version="8.*" />
```

**Project Configuration**:
```xml
<!-- Desktop.csproj -->
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk.WindowsDesktop">
  <PropertyGroup>
    <OutputType>WinExe</OutputType>
    <TargetFramework>net8.0-windows10.0.22621.0</TargetFramework>
    <UseWinUI>true</UseWinUI>
    <WindowsPackageType>msix</WindowsPackageType>
    <WindowsPackageVersion>1.0.0.0</WindowsPackageVersion>
  </PropertyGroup>
</Project>
```

---

### 4. Desktop Data Visualization: Timeline View

**Requirement**: Display task execution Gantt chart directly in desktop window

**Implementation Options**:

#### Option A: Canvas-based (Custom Drawing)
```csharp
// MainWindow.xaml.cs
private void OnCanvasRender(CanvasControl sender, CanvasDrawEventArgs args)
{
    // Draw timeline: X-axis = time, Y-axis = tasks
    // Draw task rectangles with execution times
    // Draw deadline lines in red
    // Hit-test for mouse hover
}
```
- **Pros**: Pixel-perfect control, fast performance for 1000+ tasks
- **Cons**: More code to maintain
- **Best for**: Visualization of 100–500 tasks initially

#### Option B: DataGrid-based
```xaml
<!-- TimelineView.xaml -->
<DataGrid x:Name="TaskGrid" ItemsSource="{x:Bind ViewModel.ExecutionInstances}">
    <DataGrid.Columns>
        <DataGridTextColumn Header="Task ID" Binding="{Binding InterfaceNumber}" Width="80" />
        <DataGridTextColumn Header="Scheduled" Binding="{Binding ScheduledStartTime}" Width="120" />
        <DataGridTextColumn Header="Duration" Binding="{Binding DurationMinutes}" Width="80" />
        <DataGridTemplateColumn Header="Timeline" Width="300">
            <DataGridTemplateColumn.CellTemplate>
                <DataTemplate>
                    <Canvas Height="20" Background="Transparent">
                        <!-- Draw  task bar at calculated position -->
                        <Rectangle Fill="{Binding IsValid, Converter={StaticResource ValidityColorConverter}}"
                                   Canvas.Left="{Binding VisualOffset}" Width="{Binding VisualWidth}" />
                    </Canvas>
                </DataTemplate>
            </DataGridTemplateColumn.CellTemplate>
        </DataGridTemplateColumn>
    </DataGrid.Columns>
</DataGrid>
```
- **Pros**: Familiar tabular UI, sortable/filterable
- **Cons**: Row-based, not true Gantt
- **Best for**: Detailed task inspection

**Recommendation**: Start with Option B (DataGrid), add Canvas-based Option A for full timeline view in separate tab.

